{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Xd2XEre6RJUF9Fo62xb45Z","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Both stories are at `verifying` with no proofs. They're Tier C. Neither has `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` tag, but all their ACs are tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->`. \n\nWait, I need to check for `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` specifically. Neither story file has that tag. So by default they'd use black-box (Docker) verification.\n\nBut looking at the ACs more carefully:\n\n**14-5** - Stack-aware verify dockerfile generation. ACs are about code structure, file contents, TypeScript compilation, test passing. All CLI-verifiable.\n\n\n**14-6** - Subagent status ownership + time budget. ACs about function exports, function behavior, file contents, compilation, tests. All CLI-verifiable.\n\nBoth stories are fundamentally about source code changes that can be verified by examining files and running tests, not runtime behavior that would require Docker containers. The process says to use Docker if the unit-testable tag isn't present, but that seems like it would fail here since these are code-structure verification stories rather than runtime behavior stories. I should follow the documented process, though I'm concerned Docker verification might not be the right fit for these particular stories.\n\nI've got about 30 minutes total and it's already been a few minutes reading through files. Docker verification is slow and complex, plus I need to leave time for the retro. Let me focus on one story—14-5 is Tier C with no proof yet, so that's a good candidate to tackle. The ACs are all marked as CLI-verifiable, which means they can be checked by running commands directly, but since they don't have the unit-testable tag, the process would normally push toward Docker. However, using Docker to verify code-structure acceptance criteria like Rust Dockerfile generation and PATH configuration seems inefficient when CLI commands would suffice.\n\nThe remaining ACs cover Node.js, Python, TypeScript, multi-stack Dockerfiles, npm builds and tests, and line count limits—all things I can validate by running the build, tests, and checking file contents without needing Docker infrastructure. Story 14-6 is similar, mostly about function existence and behavior. I'm tempted to add the unit-testable tag to both and skip Docker, but the process says I shouldn't do that without the tag already present. Given my time crunch, I should just follow the process and start Docker verification for 14-5, then handle any infrastructure issues as they come up.\n\nActually, I need to be realistic about the time constraint. I have about 27 minutes left and need 5 for the retro, so I should focus on just one story. Let me go with 14-5 and start the verification process now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2253,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6879,"cache_read_input_tokens":40171,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6879},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"97e0b69d-7780-4d92-a428-95a4b19f3ed1","uuid":"c2978d8e-a349-4f60-99ba-d51617e8e774"}
